Second line empty

Building a social AR platform where users drop 3D content onto real-world GPS coordinates sounds straightforward on paper. Fetch nearby content, render it in a camera view, done. I spent about six months building CityCanvas — think of it as a graffiti wall for the physical world, except the "paint" is 3D objects and AR overlays tied to specific lat/lng coordinates — and I got a surprising number of things wrong along the way. Here's what actually surprised me, and what I'd do differently.

## The spatial query problem hit me way later than it should have

My first instinct was to store lat/lng as plain floats in Postgres and do bounding box math in application code. This works until you have more than a few hundred rows and you're running queries every time a user moves.

```sql
-- What I started with (don't do this)
SELECT * FROM ar_content
WHERE lat BETWEEN $1 AND $2
AND lng BETWEEN $3 AND $4;
```

This isn't terrible for a prototype, but it's not using any index efficiently, and the moment you want "find everything within 200 meters of this point" you're doing haversine in your app layer, which gets ugly fast.

Switching to PostGIS was the right call, but it took me longer than it should have because I kept thinking "I'll add it when I need it." By the time I needed it, I had to migrate existing data and retrofit the schema.

```sql
-- What I should have started with
ALTER TABLE ar_content ADD COLUMN geom geography(Point, 4326);

UPDATE ar_content
SET geom = ST_SetSRID(ST_MakePoint(lng, lat), 4326)::geography;

CREATE INDEX ar_content_geom_idx ON ar_content USING GIST(geom);

-- Now queries are actually fast and semantically correct
SELECT id, title, content_type, lat, lng,
  ST_Distance(geom, ST_MakePoint($1, $2)::geography) AS distance_meters
FROM ar_content
WHERE ST_DWithin(
  geom,
  ST_MakePoint($1, $2)::geography,
  200  -- meters
)
ORDER BY distance_meters
LIMIT 50;
```

`ST_DWithin` on a geography column with a GiST index is dramatically faster than anything I was doing in application code. The `geography` type (as opposed to `geometry`) also handles the curvature of the earth correctly, which matters when your users are scattered across different cities.

Supabase ships with PostGIS enabled — you just need to run `CREATE EXTENSION IF NOT EXISTS postgis;` and you're good. If you're building anything location-based, do this on day one.

## GPS accuracy is genuinely bad indoors and near tall buildings

This one embarrassed me. I tested almost entirely in open suburban areas during development, where GPS is reasonably accurate. When I started testing in dense urban environments — which is literally the target use case — the experience was awful.

A user would drop AR content "here" and then walk five meters away, turn around, and the content would appear to float in the wrong spot or jump around. The GPS signal was bouncing off buildings, multipath interference is real, and the Web Geolocation API gives you an `accuracy` value in meters that most developers (including me) completely ignore.

```javascript
navigator.geolocation.watchPosition(
  (position) => {
    const { latitude, longitude, accuracy } = position.coords;

    // I was ignoring accuracy entirely. Don't.
    if (accuracy > 30) {
      // GPS is too noisy to place content reliably
      showAccuracyWarning(accuracy);
      return;
    }

    updateUserPosition(latitude, longitude);
  },
  (error) => console.error(error),
  {
    enableHighAccuracy: true,
    maximumAge: 1000,
    timeout: 10000
  }
);
```

Beyond just filtering by accuracy, I ended up implementing a simple Kalman filter to smooth position estimates over time. There are lightweight JS implementations you can adapt. The improvement in perceived stability was significant — content stopped jumping around as the user moved.

The bigger lesson is that "location-based" features need to be designed around the reality of mobile GPS, not around what GPS looks like in ideal conditions. Your UX needs to handle bad accuracy gracefully, not just pretend the number is always reliable.

## Three.js in a mobile camera AR context is not the same as Three.js in a browser

I had experience with Three.js for web-based 3D visualizations. AR felt like a natural extension — just put the canvas on top of a video element showing the camera feed, right?

The part I underestimated: you need to correctly transform 3D world coordinates (the GPS position of an AR object) into screen-space coordinates based on where the user is and which direction they're facing. This requires:

1. Device orientation (compass heading + pitch/roll via DeviceOrientationEvent)
2. The user's current GPS position
3. The GPS position of the target AR object
4. A camera in Three.js with a matching field of view

The math to convert GPS delta → bearing → 3D scene position is not complicated, but the number of degrees-of-freedom that can be wrong is large. Compass heading on Android vs iOS behaves differently. The `alpha` value from `DeviceOrientationEvent` is relative to magnetic north on some devices and true north on others, and the API doesn't tell you which.

```javascript
function gpsToScenePosition(userLat, userLng, targetLat, targetLng) {
  const R = 6371000; // Earth radius in meters
  const dLat = (targetLat - userLat) * (Math.PI / 180);
  const dLng = (targetLng - userLng) * (Math.PI / 180);

  // Approximate flat-earth offset in meters (fine within ~1km)
  const x = dLng * R * Math.cos(userLat * Math.PI / 180);
  const z = -dLat * R; // Negative because Three.js Z points toward viewer

  return new THREE.Vector3(x, 0, z);
}

// Then in your render loop, you update the camera rotation
// based on DeviceOrientationEvent alpha/beta/gamma values
function updateCameraFromDeviceOrientation(alpha, beta, gamma) {
  const euler = new THREE.Euler();
  // alpha = compass heading (z-axis rotation)
  // beta = front-back tilt (x-axis)
  // gamma = left-right tilt (y-axis)
  // Order matters: 'YXZ' works better for portrait-mode camera
  euler.set(
    THREE.MathUtils.degToRad(beta),
    THREE.MathUtils.degToRad(-(alpha || 0)),
    THREE.MathUtils.degToRad(-gamma),
    'YXZ'
  );
  camera.quaternion.setFromEuler(euler);
}
```

Even with this working, compass drift and tilt-compensation issues mean you'll want a calibration step or at least a "tap to recenter" button. AR.js abstracts a lot of this, but for a custom setup you're building it yourself.

## PWA vs Capacitor: I went back and forth more than I should have

CityCanvas works as a PWA and I also wrapped it with Capacitor for native builds. My initial assumption was "PWA is fine, I'll add Capacitor later if needed." What I learned: if you know you'll eventually want native, design for it from the start.

The camera API is the main pain point. `getUserMedia` in a browser context on iOS has gotten much better since Apple improved PWA camera support, but Capacitor gives you access to native camera plugins that handle permissions more gracefully and give you better control over camera resolution and frame rate for performance-sensitive AR rendering.

The other issue is background geolocation and device orientation events. In a PWA on iOS, the browser can throttle or restrict `DeviceOrientationEvent` when the page isn't focused. In a native Capacitor build, you have more consistent access.

If I were starting over, I'd build the core logic completely framework-agnostic (just TypeScript modules), use the PWA as the development target, and treat Capacitor as a deployment target — not as an afterthought I'm bolting on at the end.

## Text-to-3D generation is genuinely useful but the output needs triage

I integrated Meshy AI's API so users can type a prompt like "ancient stone lantern" and get a 3D model back to place in AR. This is the feature users find most exciting in demos.

The practical problems: generation takes 30-90 seconds, models come back at varying poly counts, and the textures are sometimes completely wrong for outdoor viewing where the lighting changes. I had to build a processing pipeline that checks poly count and auto-decimates if it's above a threshold (Three.js's `SimplifyModifier` or doing it server-side with a tool like `gltf-transform`).

Also: file sizes. Meshy returns GLB files. Some of them are 8-12MB. For a mobile AR app where users might be on cellular, that's a problem. I cache aggressively and added lazy loading so distant objects don't fully download until the user gets within a threshold distance.

## The actual lesson I keep coming back to

Everything I got wrong shared a common pattern: I optimized for the demo case (clear skies, good GPS, strong WiFi, flat terrain, nearby objects) and didn't design around the real-world case (urban canyons, weak signal, users on 4G, content 150 meters away that may or may not be visible).

Location-based features are fundamentally about dealing with uncertainty. GPS is uncertain. Compass heading is uncertain. Whether a user can actually see a specific real-world location from where they're standing is uncertain. Good UX for this domain means surfacing that uncertainty gracefully — showing accuracy indicators, having fallbacks when sensors misbehave, and not overclaiming precision you don't have.

The tech stack (PostGIS for spatial queries, Three.js for rendering, Capacitor for native) is fine. The hard parts are the edge cases in the physical world that you can only discover by testing in the actual environments your users will be in.

If you're building something similar, go spend time in a downtown core with tall buildings on all sides, open your app, and watch everything fall apart. Then fix it. That's the fastest way to learn what actually matters.

---

I wrote a more detailed guide on my blog covering the full architecture, the Kalman filter implementation, and the Capacitor setup for camera access: https://mcw999.github.io/mcw999-hub/blog/city-canvas-guide/
